column168: Upon inbound inspection of car NATX302108 from the BNSf railway on 3-5-08 at 1610 hours inspector found the liquid leaking from bottom outlet cap. Cap was not wrench tight and the bottom valve operating handle was open 3/4 of the way allowing product to leak into the cap. Valve handle was placed in the closed posistion and then 2 plastic quick ties were used to secure the handle in the closed posistion.  Bottom outlet cap was then tightened with 36 inch pipe wrench stopping leak.
column169: proper inspection of bottom outlet operating handles and seal bottom outlet safety pin with a seal so it do not vibrate out. Use proper tool to tighten the bottom outlet cap.

column168: BNSF delivered on the 402 yesterday Sat 3-1-08 UTLX208108 load tank car of ethanol.  Upon inbound inspection by the CCT forces the cars was found to be leaking from the top manway cover.    Cause of the leak was the Numbers 3 and 6 manway cover bolts were loose and the numbers 4 and 5 manway cover bolts were not engaged with the manway cover in the area of the hinge. Numbers 2 and 7 bolts were only hand tight. There only bolt that was wrench tight was the # 1 bolt with the seal in it. Bolts were placed back on the cover and the other bolts tightened. Leak was repaired 3-2-08 at 1245 hours.    All other fitting on the car were checked and they were ok.
column169: properly secure manway cover bolts, remedial training for plant personel

column168: 3/4/08: At approximately 10:30AM, conductor of CR crew PR-61 noted wetness/running liquid on sides of tank car UTLX 201085, load Acetone, 3, UN 1090, PG II, RQ, while performing routine yard switching at Conrail's Pt. Reading (NJ) Yard.    Determined leak was originating from underneath the breadbox.  Original shipper's seal "0365171" removed at time of inspection by local emergency response services (Middlesex County Hazardous Materials Unit) and CR emergency response contractor REACT Environmental Services.  Noted the 3" threaded liquid valve was very loose on its connection to the mounting base (noted to be approximately 2 threads from being totally unsecured).  Valve required 5 full turns to totally secure valve, whereby ceasing the leak.      Reside of product that hadn't evaporated was cleaned from car by REACT Env. Serv. personnel.  Car deemed secured by Pt. Reading (NJ) Fire Department Incident Commander/Fire Chief, at 12:20PM.  Estimated approximately 6 gallons released (captured in pails as it dripped under car from top).  Captured product and used chemical absorbant pads removed and secured in 55-gallon open head drum and awaiting disposal.

column168: Veolia ES Technical Solutions (Veolia) picked up a shipment of various hazardous materials from a customer that included a 5-gallon plastic container of Pyridine liquid.  While in transit, the container fell over and approximately 1.5 gallons of liquid leaked from the bung while the container was on its side.  The leak was discovered when the truck arrived at the Veolia transit facility located in Baytown, Texas.  Veolia personnel immediately responded by absorbing any liquid that was on the floor of the trailer and placing the leaking container in a salvage drum.  All contaminated absorbent was also containerized for future disposal.  No material was released outside of the trailer to the ground.
column169: The driver has been retrained on the need to verify proper closure of containers prior to transport.  The driver has also been retrained on the need for proper load securement.  The shipper has also been made aware of these recommendations.

column168: A van trailer operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services accpted for transportation a shipment of hazardous waste for disposal.  During the course of the trip, the vehicle was stored temporarily at Clean Harbors's location in Clevelnad, OH.  While in storage, it was determined that a small pinhole leak develpoed in the drum allowing approximately 1 gallon of material te escape from the container onto the floor of the van trailer.  It is estimated that approximatley 1 ounce escaped from the trailer onto the concrete parking area.  Facility presonel immediatley notified management and an appropriate response activity was initiated.  Facility personnel, wering appropriate personal protective equipment placed the leaking container into a suitable salvage drum and absorbed all free liquids.  This material along with the debris from the clean-up activity was placed int he salvage drum and the container was sent to the intended disposal facility for processing.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, the driver inspected the container and no evidence of damage or leaking was observed.  Drivers will continue to inspect each container as it is loaded and will take appropriate actions should a container of suspect integrity be observed.

column168: During an inspection of railcars in an outbound yard track, a BNSF railcar inspector reported a product odor emanating from one of these railcars. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder immediately inspected this track and ascertained than the odor was emanating from BRSX 9645 (DOT 112J340W tank car). The responder reported finding the protective housing cover not sealed and the A-end liquid valve had an accumulation of ice around it. Responder tool tightened both valve stem retaining nuts on this A-end liquid valve that were loose. In addition, the responder found three valve closure plugs that were 6 to 8 turns loose and these were also tool tightened. After all securement was completed by 0655 hrs. PST, 3/03/08, no further residue product odor was evident.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While moving freight at the BAX Global Inc. facility, 1 fibreboard box, which contained one (1) 1-liter bottle of Alcohols, nos, was damaged.  Apparently, the box had been struck by a forklift during handling on the dock.  BAX Global, Inc. personnel performed the cleanup using, gloves, googles, mask, broom, and a shovel, and placed down 8-12 absorbents blankets and 3 absorbent pads to contain and cleanup the release.  The spent absorbent material was placed into one (1) 25-gallon salvage drum, to be held in the OSD, pending disposition.  Approximately 10 pounds of waste were generated.  BAX Global, Inc. will coordinate disposal/disposition of the salvage drum, per local, state, and federal regulations.  No injuries or exposures reported.  No state or local agencies were notified.
column169: Since the release was accidental, and appears to be related to a forklift puncture, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.  BAX Global Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: APPROX 0200/3-1-08/ SATURDAY, MINNEAPOLIS DRIVER NOTIFIED ME THAT THERE WAS POWDER ON THE FLOOR OF 451042H, PALLET WAS PLACED ON THE 20 DOCK. POWDER IN TRAILER WAS CONTAINED. POWDER UNDER SKID WAS CONTAINED. LIFTED PALLET UP & COUND NOT LOCATE POINT OF SPILLAGE. AT THIS POINT, NO LEAK WAS PRESENT. SKID WAS MOVED TO 16 DOCK. MONDAY MORNING, DAY SHIFT MOVE THE SKID TO THE 24 DOCK TO GET OUT OF THE WAY OF THE INBOUND SHIFT. WESTERN POWDER WAS CALLED FOR DISPOSITION. THEY ASKED FOR PICTURES AND DETERMINE WHAT CAUSED THE SPILL. THIS WOULD BE DONE AFTER THE OUTBOUND SHIFT MONDAY OR TUESDAY MORNING. TUESDAY MORNING, SKID MOVED TO TRAILER IN 26 DOCK. GARY WAS MOVING TIRES IN THE AREA THE SKID WAS SETTING. WHEN HE PULLED THE FORK BLADES OUT FROM UNDER THE TIMES, A FIRE STARTED. GARY EXTINGUISHED THE FIRE AND NOTICED RESIDUE OF POWDER ON THE FLOOR.  THE SKID OF POWDER HAD LEAKED AGAIN BUT WAS NOT DEFECTED. SKID OF FIBERBOARD DRUMS WERE TAKEN OFF THE PALLET. LEAKING DRUM WAS FOUND WITH A 2" PUNCTURE HOLE IN THE BOTTOM. TOO SMALL FOR A FORK BLADE AND NO NAILS PRESENT WHERE IT WAS PLACED ON THE PALLET. HOLE WAS DIRECTLY OVER A SLAT ON THE PALLET. APPEAR A BROKEN BOARD MAY HAVE PUSHED SUP UNDER THE DRUM & PUNCHER THE DRUM. NO BURRS FOUND ON THE FORK BLADES AT SIOUX FALLS OR RAPID CITY.
column169: CONTRACTED WESTERN POWDERS. SUGGESTION WAS MADE TO START USING CHEP PALLET. THESE PALLETS HAVE MORE SLATS ON TOP & ARE ABOUT 1 1/2 INCH APART. SLATS ON PALLETS FOR THIS SHIPMENT HAVE APPROX 3" SPACE BETWEEN THEM AND ALLOW THE DRUM TO BULDGE BETWEEN THE SLATS. ALSO SUGGESTED PLACING CARDBOARD BETWEEN THE PALLET & DRUM. LOCALLY, AFTER SETTING DOWN WITH THE 2 SUPERVISORS. WE DETERMINED, ALTHOUGH THE POWDER GUIT LEAKING, THE PALLET SHOULD HAVE BEEN TAKEN APART AND THE LEAKING DRUM SHOULD HAVE BEEN REMOVED & CONTAINED IN A RECOVERY PAIL. IT IS EVIDENT THAT THE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED IN RAPID CITY WHEN IT WAS LANDED AND THE VIBRATION WHILE TRAVELING ALLOWED THE POWDER TO SEEP PAST THE SLAT. THE LEAKAGE WAS NOT NOTICED AT THE SIOUX FALLS TERMINAL, BUT THEN MOVED FROM THE 16 DOCK TO THE 24 DOCK IT STARTED AGAIN UNDETECTED.

column169: PROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES MUST BE FOLLOWED EACH TIME WHEN LOADING PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.PAILS, CYLINDERS, BAGS AND DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOODOR MTY PALLETS. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. PLACE CUSHION BETWEEN ROWS AND LAYERS OF CHEMICALS TO PREVENT OTHER OR ADJACENT FREIGHT TO EASILY DAMAGED. TRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT. DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ONTOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column168: The shipment was booked with the following 6 items of hazardous material for loading on the Hapag-Lloyd Container Line vessel Rome Express from Houston to Alexandria.    - UN1710, Trichloroethylene Solution, Class 6.1, PG III  - UN1133, Adhesives, Class 3, FP -5C, PG II, Ltd Qty  - UN1133, Adhesives, Class 2, FP -26C, PG II, Ltd Qty  - UN1950, Aerosols, Class 2.2, Ltd Qty  - UN1950, Aerosols, Class 2.1, Ltd QTy  - UN1950, Aerosols, Class 2.2 (6.1) (Max 1 liter)    The shipper advised Hapag-Lloyd after the vessel had sailed from Houston of additional hazardous material (UN1044, Fire Extinguishers, Class 2.2) in the container that was not originally booked or otherwise identified.    The shipping papers that accompanied the freight container to the marine terminal did not indicate the presence of the additional hazardous material, and the container was not placarded and/or marked to reflect the presence of the additional item.    The shipper subsequently provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd.

column168: On 03-17-08 at 0730 container SMLU 781706 was discovered leaking. The shipper, Seaboard Marine, contracted Cliff Berry LTD. to conduct the hazardous materials cleanup.  Two 275 gallon totes of d-Limonene were found leaking from the bottom outlet valve.  The valves had been left partially open. The liquid made its way through the valve and through the valve cap.  The valves were closed and caps were tightened. The spilled material was cleaned and disposed of properly. Two of the three hazardous materials being shipped were not listed on the waybill.  These two were 82 plastic bags of Sodium Hydroxide, solid weighing 23.23 kg each and 4 -  275 gallon totes of d-Limonene.  Listed were the 44 drums of Sodium Hydrosulfite. The corrections were made on the waybill.
column169: Make sure that valves are in the closed position and that caps are tightened when installed.

column168: ATA Airlines (based in Oakland CA) sent a fuel component via FedEx that was not declared HazMat.  This shipment arrived in our facitliy (Lufthansa Technik Logistik America - FLL) on March 20th which we determined the unit was a undeclared Hazmat Shipment.   I contacted ATA Airlines, Roy Cooper - HazMat Compliance Specialist, on March 20th to advise them of this error.    The details of this shipment are outlined below:  FedEx 792024093932  ATA RO 2830195025R  PN 2670136  SN 16333    ATA contacted the FAA, and, in turn, Veronica Laughlin contacted me on Friday, March 21st to discuss the sequence of events.  Per her request, I forward an email detailing these events and supporting photos.  On March 25, Ms. Laughlin came to our office and photographed the container and the unit.
column169: I would recommend that ATA offer a DGR familiarization course and see if their data base is correctly flagged to indicate potential dangerous goods.

column168: On 03/12/2008 at 16:24 Mr. Jesue Ruiz with the Tampa Port Authority discovered TILX 318103, a loaded tank car of Alcohols, N.O.S. leaking from the Pressure Relief Valve.  The car was isolated and the shipper, local agencies and State were notified.  Chemtrec report number is 2008-03-12-00165.  SWS, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the tank car to be shell full.  Contractor personnel off loaded 400 gallons of product into drums and cleaned up spilled material. The leak was secured and the car released for transport. column168: UTLX 203606 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported with a product slosh emanating from the manway area during normal switching operations in the railyard. Movement was stopped and UTLX 203606 was cordoned off in the railyard until inspection by a BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder was initiated. Responders reported that the manway cover was sealed and all securement bolts were tool tight. Further inspection revealed that the manway gasket was missing. A new manway gasket was applied and the manway was resecured. The original manway seal was reused. Securement was completed on 3/13/08 at approximately 1300 hrs. CDT. All spillage on the side shell evaporated and no product ground impact was evident.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Downstown Airport, 339 Harding Highway, Vineland, New Jersey O8360 contracted our company, Casie Ecology Oil Salvage, Inc., also of Vineland, New Jersey to transport (5) five drums of EPA listed U279 waste to the Cycle Chem, Inc. facility in Elizabeth, New Jersey. On March 4, 2008 the drums were transported and off loaded at the Casie facility and placed in a contained RCRA storage area for 10 day transfer. According to the driver that transported the drums and the supervisor at our facility, the drums were not leaking at the time of initial transport and were not leaking when received for storage and transfer. Two (2) drums however were corroded at the base ring. Apparently, upon off loading and storage of the drums for transfer, the movement caused the drums to seep the material onto the pavement. Upon discovery, all five(5) drums were immediately overpacked to prevent further seepage or discharge. The drums are now enviro mentally safe for transport to the receiving facility.
column169: The incident was discussed with all of the company truck drivers on Saturday, March 8, 2008 at our annual OSHA 8 hour refresher training. The drivers were instructed to inspect all drums thoroughly prior to transport foiany damage, defects, or leaks. Also to call the dispatcher if any defects are discovered so as to be able to provide overpacks or new drums prior to transport.

The hazmat description given is not correct. It is a fake description that had to be used because the DOT electronic submission of data rules require this information. We do not actually have the information since this was an undeclared shipment. What we do know is that the driver making the deliver  y saw 5.1 Oxidizer labels on the freight during the delivery. He questioned ABF on why this material did not require a hazmat shipping paper. We have the same question but there is no reasonable explanation so it is being reported as an undeclared shipment. We have forwarded all information to the o  rigin terminal so they can speak directly with the shipper about this shipment.

column168: 3/20/08: North Yard, Detroit, MI: At approximately 7pm, CR crew FD28 was moving tank car DMIX 300105, load Alcohols, NOS, 3, UN 1987, PG II, from track NR14 to NY11.  Crew noted car to be leaking liquid from the top of the car while car was under movement.  Product appeared to be evaporating as i ran down the sides of the car.  Car safely isolated.    CR Mgr. Risk Mgmt. A. Richter was notified, and further contacted emergency response contractor Eagle Construction, Findlay, OH, to respond.  Eagle's initial inspection found the securement seal for the bread box broken.  Upon opening the car, it was noted that all valves/fittings had been removed and replaced with either solid closure plugs, or blind closure flanges.  However, the 4-bolt blind closure flange for the 3" liquid eduction line was missing all four bolts, and not secured over the liquid eduction opening.    All four bolts were replaced the following morning of Friday, 3/21/08; liquid line blind closure flange secured, and all other fittings inspected to insure proper securement.  This car is being held at North Yard until FRA Movement Authority is obtained by the shipper, ADM Transportation Company, Decatur, IL, for movement to original destination, RKA Terminals, Romulus, MI, as car has not been leak tested in accordance with regulatory requirements.

column168: On 3-26-08 our driver (Brian Kelder) was returning from having unloaded his trailer at a customer location in Tn.when he was stopped at a weigh station. He was asked to pull around to the rear for a routine level 2 inspection. the inspector smelled Ammonia at the trailer and at that time callled Fire and hazmat.Our driver could not amell the leak. The inspector would not allow our driver (with proper PPE) to go back to the truck to find and stop the leak. When hazmat arrived they tested the area around the truck at 10 PPM, said there was no danger and returned to their station. We dispatched our Field Service unit to the site to correct the problem. He arrived and pulled the pressure off of the pump which stopped the leak (took app. 5 minutes). the driver was told he could leave and he returned to the plant at Columbus, Ga. The pump was rebuilt at the plant.  The leak point was from a weep hole in the bottom of the bearing housing on the truck pump. The hole allows any leak from the pump seal to escape and not do damage to the bearing.There was a small seal leak which was escaping from this weep hole. The trailer was empty of liquid and only had residual vapor pressure. The tank was isolated from the pump by an internal valve so any vapor in the tank could not get to the pump to escape from the leak. the pressure on the tank was 60 psi and the pressure on the pump was the same.The duration of the leak was 4 hours and 18 minutes.
column169: If allowed the driver could have stopped the leak by a simple rotation of the pump shaft.

column168: At approximately 12:10 pm on 03-12-08 it was discovered that a poly open top bin of Hazardous Waste, Filter Cake was leaking at the bottom near the legs of the bin.  The leaks were coming from holes where the bin, #LA-095, teeter bar was attached and also from areas on the legs where there are small cracks in the poly legs.  The bin was in a containment tray and the leak was very slow and the product was crystalizing as it came out.  A spill clean up company, CTI, was called and responded to handle the spill.   Approximately two pounds total came out of the container based on visual determination after the spill was cleaned.      The bin began its journey when it was picked up at the customer on 02-28-08 and was delivered to the LA warehouse on the same day. It was then shipped from LA to PX on 03-06-08 and arrived in PX on 03-07-08. The container continued on its journey as planned to the TSDF on 03-14-08 after it was placed into another poly open top bin.
column169: The ChemCare Hazardous Waste Operations Manager is in the process of taking out of service the older bins and has already ordered new bins as replacements.

column169: PROPER LOADING TECHNIQUES MUST BE FOLLOWED EACH TIME WHEN LOADING DRUMS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS IN DRUMS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MTY PALLETS. WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED. REMOVE AND AVOID OBSTRUCTIONS IN LANE OF TRAVEL TO PREVENT DAMAGE AND UNSAFE SITUATIONS. PLACE CUSHION BETWEEN ROWS AND LAYERS OF CHEMICALS TO PREVENT OTHER OR ADJACENT FREIGHT TO EASILY DAMAGED. TRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT. DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING, IT WAS DISCOVERED A DRUM OF POWDER WAS FOUND CRUSHED POSSIBLY FROM A FORKLIFT PUSHING THE DRUM INTO OTHER FREIGHT, A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE SUBSTANCE WAS RELEASED AND WAS CLEANED UP. THE AFFECTED MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO A PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED SALVAGE DRUMS. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A LINED SALVAGE DRUM PENDING DISPOSITION.
column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT,WHEN USING BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING. ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS! PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING.

column169: DISCUSS WITH THE SHIPPER ON THE IMPORTANCE OF MAKING SURE PACKAGING TOTES CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS,CHEMICALS AND LIQUID MUST BE SAFE FOR TRANSPORTING AND TRAVELING. LIDS AND OTHER CLOSURES MUST BE TIGHT TO PREVENT LIDS FROM LOOSENING, RELEASING THE LIQUID. THE DURABILITY OF THE TOTE MUST BE ABLE MAINTAIN AND CONTAIN THE LIQUIDS OR POWDERS FROM SEAPING OUT. IT IS IMPORTANT THAT TOTES ARE CHECKED BY SHIPPER AND TESTED TO ENSURE THAT PACKAGE DETERIORATION HAS NOT OCCURRED. IMPORTANT THAT LIDS AND TOPS OF PACKAGES ARE SECURE AND TIGHTENED BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE. TOTES AND DRUMS WITH VALVES MUST BE SAFELY CLOSED AND THE CONTAINER,PACKAGING, MUST BE DURABLE TO ENSURE NO LIQUID OR POWDER IS ALLOWED TO BE RELEASED. DISCUSS WITH SHIPPER ONPROPER, SAFE AND RELIABLE PACKAGING TO PREVENT EASY RELEASE OF PRODUCT. PACKAGING OF CHEMICALS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND LIQUIDS MUST BE THOROUGHLY INSPECTED BEFORE IT LEAVES ORIGIN!

The shipment was offered to Hapag-Lloyd from Savannah, Georgia to Antwerp, Belgium on the Leverkusen Express as non-hazardous cargo.    The shipper advised Hapag-Lloyd after the vessel sailed from Savannah of undeclared hazardous materials loaded in the container.    The shipping papers that accompained the container did not indicate the presence of hazardous materials, and the container was no placarded and/or marked.    The shipper subsequentially provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd.    Hapag-Lloyd advised the planner and Master of the vessel of the undeclared hazardous materials onboard.

column168: UTLX 650259 (DOT 111A100W3 tank car) on the APA (Apache Railway Co.) interchange track was reportedly rejected for interchange by APA due to dried product residue on its side shell. BNSF contract responders inspected UTLX 650259 finding 4 of 8 of the manway securement bolts only hand tight. Further inspection revealed that the manway gasket was deteriorated with compression cuts and gasket pieces missing. The product outage was checked and deemed appropriate. The responders applied a new manway gasket and properly secured the manway lid. The dried residue on the shell was neutralized and water washed. Response was concluded by 1330 hrs. MDT on 3/19/08.

column168: An inbound BNSF train inspection in the railyard revealed BN 875053 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) leaking product from the bottom outlet auxiliary valve configuration. BN 875053 was switched out of the train, carefully moved and isolated in the railyard with a containment pool place under this tank car. This bottom outlet auxiliary valve configuration is a  center T-piping arrangement with extensions and an end cap that extend to either side of the bottom of this tank car for unloading purposes. A cracked flange weld was observed on the right side pipe extension. Product was dripping from this weld crack at the flange connection. The top operated bottom outlet operating rod was in the closed position, but product was by-passing the closed valve into the bottom T-piping. On 4/01/08, the product (company material diesel fuel) in BN 875053 was transferred into a BNSF fuel service provider's fuel trucks and earmarked for local BNSF usage. BN 875053 will be scheduled and sent to a qualified repair facility for the auxiliary T-pipe fitting removal and repairs to the top operated bottom outlet valve. The tank qualification for BN 875053 was completed in the year 2000 and due in 2010.

column168: The driver arrived at the customer’s site at 0945 and positioned his vehicle at the unloading area. The unloading hoses were connected from the intermediate bulk container, (IBC) to be offloaded and the unloading pump. A second hose was connected between the threaded discharge outlet of the pump coupling and the customers receiving tank. The employee secured and inspected all connections ensuring that there were no leaks. Upon receiving approval to begin offloading the employee activated the offloading pump by engaging the air. As the unloading process began the threaded discharge coupling between the pump and the receiving tank cracked causing approximately 15 gallons of sodium hydroxide solution to be released into the immediate area. The employee shut down the transfer pump stopping the flow. While doing this, the unloading employee was splashed with sodium hydroxide solution originating from the cracked fitting. The employee was moved to a safety shower and rinsed off. The employee was subsequently transported to  MetroHealth Hospital, Cleveland OH,  for medical evaluation. The employee was treated at the hospital for superficial chemical burns to the right and left thigh & a small superficial chemical burn to the neck. The employee was admitted to the hospital for further observation by the treating physician. The employee was released the following day and returned to work on a restricted basis. Facility employees cleaned up the area affected by the release. The recovered material was containerized for subsequent disposal at a licensed, permitted disposal facility. The  transport unit was returned to the shipping facility for further examination. The failed coupling was examined and it was determined that the weight of the material in the transfer hose in conjunction with the pressure of the discharge pump contributed to the failure of the threaded coupling. To prevent future occurrences, a non threaded coupling was installed on the discharge port of the pump. This incident was reviewed with affected facility personnel and also at a facility safety meeting.
column169: To prevent future occurrences, a non threaded coupling was installed on the discharge port of the pump. This incident was reviewed with affected facility personnel and also at a facility safety meeting.

column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases.  For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers (responsible party) are requested to respond, repair and remediate.  By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the same organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence.  After each NAR incident, KCSR provides outreach to the shipper to help investigate root-cause factors for correction.  For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be contacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: The shipment was offered to Hapag-Lloyd from Long Beach, California on the New York Express as non-hazardous cargo.    The shipper advised Hapag-Lloyd after the vessel sailed from Long Beach of undeclared hazardous material loaded in the container.    The shipping papers that accompanied the container did not indicate the presence of hazardous materials, and the container was not placarded and/or marked.    The shipper subsequently provided correct hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd.    Hapag-Lloyd advised the Master of the vessel of the undeclared hazardous materials onboard.

column168: On March 23, 2008 at 02:30 hours, personnel in the CSXT S+N Yard in Montgomery, AL discovered GATX 32964, a loaded tank car of Flammable Liquid, N.O.S had a slosh leak around the top of the tank car. GATX 32964 was isolated and the shipper, Weyerhaeuser Co. was notified by Chemtrec (Report # 20080323-00003). SWS Environmental First Response, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the yard and found that GATX 32064 had four of eight manway bolts where less than tool tight and that the manway gasket was deteriorated. SWS replaced the manway gasket, secured the manway properly and wiped off the top of tank car. SWS reported that no product had made contact with the ground. The car was released for transport and disposition.  Cause Code: 200  NARRI: 5(5+5+0) X (2+0) = 100

column168: Commercial tanker motor vehicle was northbound on 191 Chicopee, MA. Veh #2 coming of entrance ramp lost power,tried to restart by "popping" clutch, lost control and coasted into travel lane striking Veh #3 causing Veh # 2 to contact CTMV. Driver of CTMV tried to avoid Veh #2 resulting in tank rolling over, igniting and exploding. Tractor was engulfed in flames. Driver was able to undo seat belt and exit cab walking through flames and awaiting emergency responders. Driver succumbed to injuries. Emergency response provided by Chicopee and West Springfield Fire Departments and MA State Police. Tanker also contained 1000 gallons Diesel Fuel, Combustible Liquid, NA 1993 PG 111.
column169: This was a tragic accident where the driver of veh #2 was cited for negligence and possible vehicular homicide. There was nothing our professional driver could have done to prevent the accident.

column62: Inadequate Preparation for Transportation; Loose Closure, Component, or Device
column168: UNIVAR USA Inc. driver picked up 1 portable tank from Snap Fasteners at 302 Factory Ave. Lawrenceburg, KY on 03/10/2008, after the customer loaded the portable tank onto UNIVAR USA Inc. vehicle the driver inspected the tank for data and proper labeling. Driver secured freight and returned to 6800 Enterprise Dr. Louisville, KY. Upon return to 6800 Enterprise Dr. the driver discovered that the dome/manway cover on the portable tank was dislodged from the clamp ring allowing approximately 6 gallons to leak from the portable tank. The local UNIVAR USA Inc. Haz Whopper team secured the dome/manway, contained and absorbed the spilled material. All materials used in the clean-up were disposed of as Hazardous Waste. Upon investigation it was determined that the clamp ring securing the dome/ manway cover to the portable tank was not tightened to proper specifications. This allowed the dome/manway cover to slip allowing contents to leak.
column169: On 03/28/2008 training was held to review the inspection of package and closure requirements with drivers and plant employees.

column168: AS THE KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC UNIT WAS TRAVELING WESTBOUND ON SHERIDAN ST, IT WAS IMPACTED IN THE RIGHT SIDE BY THE CLAIMANT VEHICLE TRAVELING AT A HIGH RATE OF SPEED. ON 03-03-08 I DEPUTY TONY AGUIRRE OF THE COLFAX COUNTY SHERIFF'S DEPT. CONTACTED MR. BRIAN WIGGS SHORTLY AFTER HIS RELELASE FROM THE HOSPITAL, HE STATED THAT HE WAS TRAVELING WESTBOUND ON U.S. 64 DESCENDING MCEVOY PASS, NEGOTIATING A SHARP RIGHT CURVE, WHICH SURPRISED HIM, HE STATED THAT HE DROVE TO THE LEFT TO COMPENSATE FOR HIS TRALERS REAR TIREDS, TOUCHED THE BRAKES AT WHICH TIME THE TGRACTOR-TANKER SLID ON SNOW/ICE COVERED ROAD-WAYS ROLLING ONTO ITS LEFT (DRIVER) SIDE OVER THE QUARD-RAIL AND DOWN THE HILL SIDE A SHORT DISTANCE COMING TO REST ON ITS RIGHT (PASSENGER) SIDE FOR 3/4'S OF A ROLL. column168: WHILE LOADING FREIGHT ADJACENT TO DRUMS, FORKLIFT WHEEL SKIDDED ON WET FLOORING AND PUNCTURED THE BOTTOM ONE DRUM.  THE AREA WAS SECURED AND THE AFFECTED DRUM SEALED INSIDE A PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED SALVAGE DRUM.
column169: APPLY FLOOR DRY TO THE TRAILER FLOOR WHEN IT IS WET AND SLIPPERY.

column168: WHEN TRAILER DOOR WAS OPENED FOR UNLOADING, WET SPOT WAS DISCOVERED ON FLOOR AND HAD APPARENTLY LEAKED FROM TOTES CONTAINING ONLY A RESIDUE OF MATERIAL THE CLOSURES WERE SECURED AND THERE WAS NO FURTHER LEAKAGE.  TOTES WERE DELIVERED TO CONSIGNEE WITHOUT EXCEPTION.
column169: INSPECT ALL FREIGHT PRIOR TO LOADING.

column168: WHEN LOADED AT ORIGIN TERMINAL A SKID WAS PLACED ON TOP OF THE TOTE. THE TOP FREIGHT SHIFTED IN TRANSIT, PUNCTURING THE TOP OF THE TOTE. HMONE WAS CALLED AND AN ER TEAM RESPONDED TO THE SITE TO SECURE THE LEAKING TOTE AND CLEAN THE SPILLAGE. THE SHIPPER IS FORWARDING A REPLACEMENT TOTE AND THE PRODUCT WILL BE TRANSFERRED WHEN THE ALTERNATE PACKAGING IS RECEIVED.
column169: TOP FREIGHT SHOULD HAVE BEEN LOADED ONTO LOGISTICS BARS ABOVE THE TOTE TO AVOID DAMAGE.

column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH AT LEAST 65 PERCENT, BUT NOT MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: THE PACKAGE WAS DROPPED DURING THE SORT ON THE FLOOR IN THE SORT CENTER AND IT BEGAN FUMING, AN ORANGE SUBSTANCE BEGAN SPILLING OVER AND THE BOX WAS BEING EATEN AWAY BY THE SUBSTANCE. DG ADMIN WAS CONTACTED AND THE STATION WAS INSTRUCTED TO CLEAR AREA, AND IT WOULD BE TREATED AS NITRIC ACID RED FUMING SINCE WE HAD NO INFORMATION AND USE THE ERG FOR EMERGENCY RESPONSE MEASURES. THE PACKAGE WAS COVERED WITH SOIL AND VERMICULITE AND IT STOPPED ERRUPTING. WE RECOVERED THE WAYBILL NUMBER AND CONTACTED THE SHIPPER AND THE CONSIGNEE FOR ASSISTANCE. THE CONSIGNEE SENT A TECHNICIAN TO THE STATION WHO NOTIFIED THE KSA. KSA SENT OVER THE MSDS SHEET FOR BOTH BOTTLES. IN THE MEAN TIME THE MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN A PLASTIC BIN WITH VERMICULITE AND DIRT UNTIL THE CLEAN UP VENDOR CONTRACTED BY KSA ARRIVEDTO PROCEED WITH CLEAN UP. UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION WE NOTED 2 BOTTLES ONE WAS BROKEN WHICH CONTAINED NITRIC ACID AND THE SECOND ONE WAS IN TACT CONTAINED HYDROCHLORIC ACID (38 OZ). THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED AND IS CURRENTLY INVESTIGATING THE COMPANY OFFICALS(KSA) ARE CURRENTLY ON SITE AT FEDEX EXPRESS SUPERVISING REMEDIATION. MR. VARGAS DID NOT SEEK MEDICAL ATTENTION NO INJURY WAS REPORTED.WHEN MR. VARGAS WAS EXPOSED HE WAS SENT IMMEDIATELY TO THE WASH STATION AND WASHED.

Customer (LabCorp) tendered cargo shipment as Medical Supplies at our SLC cargo location. The cargo employees tested the shipment for explosives and received no alarm from the material.When shipment arrived in PHX, the cargo employee noticed some small print that stated "corrosive". The opened the box to find some plastic bottles that stated Sodium Hydroxide.Southwest Airlines Safety was then notified. After further research with Devin Johnson of LabCorp, he confirmed to me that the material shipped was in fact Sodium Hydroxide.

NYK Line advised Hapag-Lloyd after vessel had sailed from Savannah that the shipments were not booked as hazardous materials, the shipping papers did not indicate the presence of hazardous materials, and that the tanks were not placarded and/or marked.  NYK subsequently provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd.    Hapag-Lloyd advised the Master of the vessel of the undeclared hazardous materials onboard.

column169: RETRAINING ON SAFE USE AND OPERATION OF THE FORKLIFT. WHEN ENTERING TRAILERS WITH PAILS, DRUMS OR TOTES LOADED AND HIDDEN BEHIND FREIGHT,WHEN USING BLADES, ENTER WITH CAUTION TO AVOID PUNCTURING PAILS. FREIGHT PLACED ON DOCK MUST BE SECURED AND PROPERLY BLOCKED AND SHROUDED TO AVOID EASY PUNCTURING FROM OTHER FREIGHT OR FORKLIFT. DISCUSS DURING PRESHIFT ON THE SAFETY OF DOCKING, REMOVING AND TRANSFERRING CHEMICAL, LIQUID AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. BEING AWARE OF SURROUNDINGS WHEN WORKING. ON THE DOCK AND WHILE TRANSFERRING PACKAGES OFCHEMICALS, LIQUIDS OR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS! PAILS OF LIQUIDS, CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BECOMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, MTY PALLETS AND PLYWOOD TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGED AND PUNCTURING. USE LOTS OF DUNNAGE TO CUSHION, SHROUD AND PROTECT ALL SIDES OF FREIGHT.

column168: March 11, 2008 an Aloha Airlines Cargo agent based in Hilo Hawaii noticed a box with the Division 2.2 hazard label on it.  After further investigation, another label was discovered stating that the box contained an inner packaging with Hydrogen Chloride was in the package.  The agent then pulled this undeclared shipment on the side and informed his/her lead agent for further disposition.    I was informed by the Hilo Cargo Supervisor of the discovery of an undeclared hazmat item on March 24, 2008 during the Aloha Airlines Train the Trainer class.  The supervisor questioned our local FAA Inspector regarding the undeclared hazmat article.  I was then brought up to date regarding this situation and thus am filin this report.    Apparently, in Hilo, the Fedex personnel delivers two drops to the Aloha Airlines Cargo facility for air transport.  The driver delivers his first drop then makes his ground service pickup and delivers the balance of outbound cargo to the Aloha Airlines cargo facilities in the afternoon.  The item in question was not declared to the Aloha Airlines staff at time of tender.  The item was tendered as an undeclared shipment and was not forwarded for air transport.

On March 11, 2008 a similar box was discovered and reported (Incident Report Number E-2008040182).  Aloha Airlines Cargo Lead Agent discovered this package with hazardous labels and markings on the box.  The cargo lead then pulled the undeclared shipment aside for further disposition.    The Fedex personnel makes two deliveries to the Aloha Airlines Cargo facility for outbound air transport.  The driver delivers his first drop to the facility then continues his ground service pickups and delivers the balance of the outbound cargo to the Aloha Airlines cargo facilities in the afternoon.  The item in questions was not declared to the Aloha Airlines cargo staff at time of tender.  The item was tendered as an undeclared shipment and was not forwarded for air transport.    Aloha was informed that our local FAA Inspector contacted the original shipper (Spectra Gas) and was informed that one of the cylinders contained an empty cylinder.  If this was so, then the cylinder was improperly identified, marked and labeled as containing a hazardous material article when in fact, it did not.

column168: On March 25, 2008, at approximately 1000 hours, a railway tankcar NATX 29986, Residue, last contained Methyl Acetate, flammable liquid, UN1231 PG II, was reported leaking during a routine inspection by Louisiana State Police (LSP) at the Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) Latanier Louisiana yard. The tank car was discovered leaking from the manway gasket which is described as vapor pressure. The shipper representative responded to the site to make repairs. There were no injuries.        CODE:209  NARRI: 5(4+3+0)x(2+0)=70
column169: On The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR), shippers are immediately notified of all HAZMAT releases.  For non-accident releases (a.k.a. package or closure defects), where possible, shippers (responsible party) are requested to respond, repair and remediate.  By immediately involving the shipper, in-depth knowledge of the release cause is gained by the same organization that can implement process changes to prevent recurrence.  After each NAR incident, KCSR provides outreach to the shipper to help investigate root-cause factors for correction.  For non-accident related releases, the shipper should be contacted directly for details associated with actions taken to prevent recurrence.

column168: On March 19, 2008 at 12:33, at the CSXT Parsons Yard, Columbus, OH, Mr. Joel Roberts, FRA, Hazmat Inspector reported NATX 29271, a residue tank car of xylenes, leaking from the vacuum relief device. The car was isolated and Chemtrec notified. Eagle Construction + Environmental Services, Inc. (ECESI), Findlay, OH, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and reported the leak was due to loose manway cover bolts. They tightened the bolts and the leak ceased. On March 20, 2008 ECESI personnel met w/ Mr. Joel Roberts, FRA, Parsons Yard, Columbus, OH and jointly inspected NATX 29271. The vacuum relief device began to vent after someone depressed its cap. the vacuum relief device was removed and a plug inserted in its stead, and the leak ceased.   NARRI:  5(4+1+0) x (2+0) = 50  Cause Code:  457

column168: An incident occurred during the course of a delivery on the noted date of this report involving the external valve on tank unit #2881. It was loaded with and in dedicated service for Ethylene Glycol. While in the process of prepping for unloading by CUSTOMER personnel, the external valve shaft was backed all the way out of the outer plate yoke and packing gland and actually came out of the valve assembly completely. As the internal valve was open, EG flowed out of the valve thru the packing gland. Only a small amount of material escaped the tank prior to internal valve EMERG shutdown. It was estimated by facility MGMT that 2-3 gallons were spilled. Material was cleaned up in house using absorbents and basic response methods.    The valve that failed in this incident was a Betts QRB Hydrolet valve model# QY763SST. Upon disassembly of the outer valve clamp and plate, the valve seat assembly was found loose in the valve body. The cotter pin that normally secures the valve seat assembly to the threaded valve shaft end was missing and was not found inside the valve body. This would lead us to believe that A. The cotter pin was installed improperly at last washing reassembly or B. the cotter pin was not installed at all.    This cargo tank is a leased unit. Lessor performs all cleaning and maint on this tank.     As a result of this incident, the leasing company was contacted regarding the incident and our findings. Corrective action measure are outlined in part VII of this report.
column169: Leasing company has been advised that as a result of this incident, we will begin routing all trailers to thier facility for valve takedown and inspection to insure we don’t have any  other hidden valve issues. This measure was instituted the day of the incident.    Formal Corrective action response from the Leasing Co. is as follows:      "I have voiced your  concerns to all corresponding departments. In addition I have been working diligently with management at our tank wash, and have implemented a new Checklist. In addition to the wash tickets already being placed on the clean tanks a form will be placed stating that all of your trailers will be checked for the following: Vac. test performed (internal/external valve), All gaskets in place, External valve assembly (including cotter pins) are complete, and Number of hoses on trailer as it leaves the wash rack. I do feel that by taking this extra step, all problems in the future will be eliminated. This will implemented immeadiatly.If you have any other concerns you would like to include on this form, please let me know, and we will add them".    Univar to spot check external valve assemblies "post cleaning" to ensure compliance.

column168: A bulk road tanker delivery of 190 proof Ethanol was unloaded to the Facilities tank farm.  An error was made by the operator in selecting which tank to connect the road tanker to.   The tank selected was partially full and the Ethanol that was off loaded caused the tank to overflow into the tank retention dike area.    When the error was discovered the off loading was stopped and emergency spill procedures were enacted. (Building electric shut down and room isolated from the rest of the facility.)    There was no fire and the leak was mostly confined to the retention dike, this was subsequently removed by a remediation crew for disposal.   Some material leaked from the retention dike due to a seal failure, this was contained in the room drain fire control tank that is located outside of the building.  This was subsequently pumped out by the remediation crew.    The waste will be disposed of at an approved EPA incinerator.      #25) Road Tanker did not have a failure.  Human error caused the storage tank to overflow.
column169: The existing unloading procedure will be reviewed with staff involved.   A level switch to shut down the loading pump will be installed to prevent overfilling.    The leaking retention dike seal will be repaired.

column168: Florida Rock & Tank Lines, Inc. driver was delivering fuel to a customer location. While unloading at a remote drop the driver noticed fuel coming out of the drop at the unleaded tank. The driver immediately shut off flow of product but approximately 10 gallons leaked onto the concrete containment area. No product reached soil or drains. Chattahoochee Environmental came to the scene. The spill was cleaned by Quick Trip personnel. It was determined that the spill was not due to overfill but due to a faulty P valve in the vapor recovery. Quick trip assumed full responsibility for spill.
column169: Mike Bridges from Quick Trip agreed to have their iternal maintenance meet us onsite for next delivery to ensure that they had repaired the faulty P valve in the vapor recovery.

column168: Schneider National Bulk Carriers' driver was unloading product into customers storage tank. There was a manhole cover located about 3 ft up from the bottom of the tank. The manhole cover did not have the bolts tightened down and as a result the product leaked out through the manhole cover until the leak was discovered. The Customer was able to tighten the bolts and stop the leak. Human error would be the root cause of the manhole cover not being secure on the storage tank.  The customer used their vacuum truck to clean up the spilled product in their containment area. Once the cover was tightened we finished unloading the product without incident.
column169: The customer associate assisting with the delivery of the product was going to talk with the indivual who had failed to secure the cover. They will also have a procedure in place for future deliveries in which the tank manhole covers will be inspected prior to unloading.

column168: Schneider National Bulk Driver reported finding product spilled in the crash box of the tank trailer during his post trip inspection. The seal at the dome lid was not sufficient which allowed product to leak out into the crash box. The driver cleaned up the product spill in the crash box. A foam sealant was put around the dome lid to provide a secure seal and the trailer continued on to the destination. The trailer has  been inspected and it has been determined that the rubber lining at the top ridge of the man hole has cracks or tears in it which resulted in it not sealing properly. The trailer is in the maintenance shop for repairs to the liner.
column169: The pre-trip inspection by the driver should include the visual inspection of the liner around the dome lid area of the trailer. The driver did not do a thorough enough inspection prior to loading the trailer. The driver has been counseled regarding this. The pre-trip inspection should have caught the liner issue and we could have avoided loading this trailer until the repairs were completed.

column168: PROX 43802 (DOT 111A100W1 tank car) was reported leaking product from the manway area during normal switching operations in the railyard. PROX 43802 was carefully moved and isolated in the railyard awaiting a detailed inspection. BNSF contract responders reported finding 2 of 6 manway securement bolts less than tool tight. Further inspection revealed that the manway cover gasket was misaligned with a section of this gasket folded over out of the gasket groove. The gasket was inspected, deemed serviceable and it was properly repositioned. The manway lid was closed and all manway securement bolts were properly tool tightened. All other valves and fittings were inspected with no other exceptions noted. New seals were applied to the manway and the valve protective housing cover. The dried (evaporated) residue product stains along with other oily residue were wiped from the side shell and the side ladders. No ground impact from this product release was evident. Response was concluded by 1115 hrs. MDT on 3/31/08.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column169: PAILS CONTAINING LIQUIDS, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND CHEMICALS MUST BE SAFELY CHECKED TO INSURE NOTHING IS ALLOWED TO LEAK OUT. THE PACKAGINGS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED USING DUNNAGE, PLYWOOD AND OR MTY PALLETS.WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING AND HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, LIQUIDS AND CHEMICALS. RECURRENT TRAINING IN HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. WHEN LOADING NOTE THAT BAGS, PAILS OR DRUMS OF LIQUIDS AHEAD. HEAVY FREIGHT LOADED ON THE BOTTOM, LIGHT FREIGHT ON TOP! USE PLENTY OF CUSHIONING BETWEEN LAYERS OF FREIGHT. DO NOT LOAD HEAVY FREIGHT ON TOP OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. FREIGHT MUST BE SECURELY BLOCKED AND BRACE BEFORE ALLOWING TO MOVE IN TRANSIT!

column168: At 23:23 hrs, 3 employees were unloading the trailer in question, separating packages received shrink-wrapped on a pallet from the customer. One package caught fire a short distance up the first conveyor belt. The employees stopped the belt and left the trailer. As the supervisor called 911 an employee used the nearest fire extinguisher to douse the flames, preventing damage to other packages or any equipment. The package was marked ORM-D, level 2 aerosols. It was the only package involved in the fire. The east primary (unload) area was evacuated. The fire department arrived at approximately 23.33 hrs and urged UPS to involve a professional fire investigator to evaluate the incident. Our professional fire investigator subsequently determined that one of the aerosols had been punctured in an impact compressing it between two adjacent cans in the box. The burn pattern indicated that only the flammable liquid component of the aerosol (containing ethanol) was involved in the fire, and that a portion of the liquid remained in the can Based on this evidence, the investigator concluded that the puncture had occurred at some time before the package was removed from the pallet on UPS

column168: On March 5, 2008, around 14:00 hours, I went to gauge Railcar UTLX 81847 with a slip tube type of gauging rod. I loosened the packing nut roughly one turn and started to pull up. The slip tube packing nut started to leak a small amount of vapor. I pushed the slip tube back down and tightened the nut, but I still detected a small leak at the packing. I then loosened the nut and pulled the slip tube all the way up and tightened the packing nut. The leak stopped at this time.    I immediately called Chemtrec to notify them that they needed to contact the shipper in response to the defective slip tube. Canadian Enterprise called soon after my call to Chemtrec. We discussed the best way to handle the problem. They suggested unloading the car of liquid and then vaporing the down the car to about 5 PSI. So that a Union Tank car repair crew could replace the packing so we could stop the leak when the slip tube was pushed down into the car for safe shipping.  After unloading the car of liquid and vaporing down to 5 PSI, I pushed the slip tube down back down into the car to see if I could get it non-leak tight. I could and I did.  then called the UTLX Repair Crew and informed them of the circumstances. They came to the site and repaired the packing at the slip tube. Then they okayed the release of the car after checking to make sure it was not leaking.  After talking to Ernie Sirotek (Business Card enclosed), I learned that the small leak around the slip tube is somewhat of a normal occurrence during the gauging process with this old-style slip tube device. W would not consider this an unintentional release due to the way these gauges operate.
column169: I would suggest eventually doing away with this old-style of gauging device would be helpful. While this style remains in service, replacing the packing more often may also address the issue. The older the rail car, the more problems occur with this kind gauging device.    Sheldon United Terminal now has a specific, personal contact at UTLX just a short distance from our plant. It is a big help as the crew is 24-hour and mobile.  I have also enclosed the repair notice from UTLX for the car and the supervisor’s business card.

THE TRUCK DRIVER, SALVADOR ROMAN MORALES, LOADED 8,000 GALLONS OF KEROSENE IN THE REFINERY SHELL CHEMICAL LOCATED AT YABUCOA, PUERTO RICO. THIS PRODUCT WAS DESTINED TO ARRIVE AT THE PHARMACEUTICAL BRISTOL MYERS IN MAYAQUES, PUERTO RICO. MR. ROMAN INDICATES THAT WHEN HE WAS DRIVING ON THE MENTIONED HIGHWAY HE FELL ASLEEP OR FELT DIZZY AND WHEN HE REALIZED IT THE TRUCK TANK WAS ALREADY DOING ZIG ZAGS AND THE TRUCK ENDED HITTING THE CEMENT FENCE THAT WAS IN THE HIGHWAY. WE RECEIVED A CALL FROM A DRIVE BY CONDUCTOR THAT WAS HELPING OUR TRUCK DRIVER, MR. ROMAN, AND SHE INFORMED US ABOUT THE ACCIDENT AND LETS US SPEAK TO THE DRIVER, MR. ROMAN, WE IMMEDIATELY STARTED TO TAKE THE NECESSARY STEPS. IMMEDIATELY, WE REQUIRED THE SERVICES OF SEVERAL COMPANIES AND THE CLEAN UP COMPANY WAS RICLEM ENVIRONMENTAL AT 787-361-4119 WITH MR. JORGE CLEMENTE AND HE TOOK CHARGE OF THE CLEAN UP. WE INFORMED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER AT 787-729-6770 TO MRS. RAWLS AND THE CASE NUMBER IS 865073. WE NOTIFIED THE FOLLOWING AGENCIES: . "COMISION DE SERVICIOS PUBLICOS" OF PUERTO RICO TO MRS. SONIA PAVELLON AT 787-756-1919. . FIRE DEPARTMENT IN JUANA DIAZ, PUERTO RICO WHICH WERE ALREADY AT THE SITE  . "JUNTA DECALIDAD AMBIENTAL" OF PONCE, PUERTO RICO AND SPOKE TO WILFREDO VARGAS AT 787-840-4070, WHICH WAS AT THE SITE AT THE MOMENT.

column168: An eastbound BNSF train was stopped on BNSF Main Track 2 at the Minnesota-Wisconsin state border. This train stop was initiated by an air hose separation towards the head end of this train. During train inspection activities, entrained OWIX 15055 (a DOT 111A100W1 tank car stopped on the Minnesota side of the state border) was observed buckled with its side shell split open approximately near the mid-tank area. The product within escaped and ran down the track embankment onto the frozen shoreline of the Mississippi River that paralleled the main tracks at this location. The root cause of the tank's failure is under investigation via metallurgical testing and evaluation. BNSF environmental contractors initiated verification sampling of the impacted areas of ground and water.  Local officials closed the U.S. Highway 10 Bridge that connects Minnesota and Wisconsin near Prescott, WI until approximately 2000 hrs. CST, 3/05/08.

This freight container containing various hazardous materials, including the subject IBC containing UN 2319. It was discovered by terminal personnel a leak originating from the subject freight container. The leaking container was placed in a mobile containment unit and isolated pending further remediation. Local police and fire agencies, as well as local port authority, were contacted. In addition, a third party environmental response contractor (Cliff Berry International) was contacted. The spill was subsequently remediated and the source of the leak identified. The subject IBC was found to have a partially closed discharge valve. This was concluded to be due to vibrations during transport. Thus, the valves were secured and then tie-strapped for safety. All recovered spill waste was handled by CliffBerry and subsequently processed for disposal by the same. The remainder of this shipment rendered safe for ocean transport and shipped accordingly. NOTE: Undeclared hazmat was discovered upon the opening of this freight container, thus, this will be reflected in a separate & subsequent report. END OF REPORT      SUPPLEMENTAL TO INITIAL REPORT(Ref. E-2008040453)Correction to Initial Report Findings:It was noted that undeclared hazmat was discovered upon the opening of the involved freight container, and that this information would be reflected in a separate and subsequent report; however, this was in fact an erroneous comment.On a separate but relevant note, an incident involving this same shipment was reported by Florida East Coast Railway ("FEC") to have occurred on 3/17/2008 at the FEC facility in Miami (Ref. E-2008030299, filed by FEC on3/24/2008). Specifically, it was reported that both a hazmat spill had occurred, and an undeclared hazmat was discovered, with the same shipment. However, it was erroneously stated on the subject report that the shipper ofrecord was Seaboard Marine LTD, when in fact it was Tintek USA, as evidenced by the actual shipping papers (See additional related information on this and the initial report).

column168: During a transfer of cargo from one freight container to another (for unrelated reasons), it was discovered that there were undeclared hazmat inside. Specifically, the shipper "load and count" freight container arrived without any indiction of its hazardous contents (i.e. no placards, no hazmat documentation). Upon discovering this issue, the container was subsequently placed on hold pending rectification of the aforementioned deficiencies. A Dangerous Goods Declaration was obtained from the shipper, and the container was placarded apppropriately. Thus, the subject shipment was rendered safe and suitable for ocean transportation. END OF REPORT
column169: The shipper may need further hazmat training to help avoid this oversight from reoccuring. END OF REPORT

Mario Aguilar, Trainmaster, reported a mist and liquid was seeping from the top of tank car GATX 32747, located fourth from the eastend, on Track 9, at 7801 Van Nuys Boulevard, Van Nuys, CA. MTO Aguilar stated the tank car has been emitting a mist while being handled during normal switching operations. No odor was being detected by yard personnel, and no liquid was on the ground. DeanCooper, Manager, Hazardous Material, responded. Manager Cooper confirmed the tank car released a small amount of material to the top area of the car, and stated the material did not reach the ground. Mr. Cooper stated the Oseco disc had been installed upside down, which contributed to the failure.The safety vent, a GATX trivent, had an inspection screw cover that was not in place, and was found laying adjacent to the safety vent,attached by a cable. Mr. Cooper further advised the damaged frangible disc was replaced with a like type disc, and the safety vent properly secured. The tank car was released for movement onto the consignee

column168: At approximately 21:07 hrs, a package that was moving on the brown belt within the Seattle hub spontaneously caught fire Flames were observed jetting from the package at an angle. The belt was stopped in a position below a sprinkler which activated and put out the fire. Employees were evacuated in response to the triggered fire alarm. The fire department responded at approximately 2115 hrs. Although the outer carton was substantially burned, subsequent examination of the package revealed that the package had been marked as a Consumer commodity, ORM-D; the inner containers were marked as Westech DM Easy, an industrial adhesive. Of the 12 aerosols in the package, one appeared to have been punctured near the base, possibly in an impact from the chime of an adjacent can. The labels of many aerosols in the package were sticky, suggesting the punctured can expelled its contents, and we suspect a static discharge ignited the gas or vapor. The operation resumed at 21:45 hrs.

column168: A van trailer operated by Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. was enrooted from the shipper’s location to the intended waste management facility. During the course of the trip, the driver made a routine stop at Clean Harbors Aragonite, UT facility where it was placed into temporary in-transit storage. During the course of storage, a 55 gallon polyethylene drive containing 19 compressed gases lecture bottles of oxygen were being moved. Please note that the container in question was being utilized as an overpack to consolidate and secure the individual cylinders for ease of handling. During the transfer operation, a “hissing sound” was heard and the equipment operator stopped the transfer operation and moved away from the container and notified the on-scene emergency coordinator. Upon arrival of the on scene emergency coordinatory, it was discovered that the lid of the polyethylene drum was forced off the drum due to an over pressurization within the overpack. The container was inspected and it was determined that the venting had stopped. The over pack was moved to an isolation room where each individual cylinder was inspected. An inspection of the cylinders indicated that one of the valves of a cylinder was partially open and that allowed the oxygen to collect in the headspace of the drum that eventually forced the lid off the container. It is estimated that the duration of the release was instantaneous once the lid was dislodged and the vapors dispersed into the atmosphere. It is believed that the release did not cause any adverse effects to the environment or the individuals handling the containers. At the conclusion of the response activities, the cylinders were secured and were sent for disposal to the intended waste management facility.
column169: Subsequent to the incident, an investigation was initiated and it was determined that the cause of the release was most likely attributed to a loose valve. Prior to transportation, each cylinder was inspected and placed into the 55 gallon polyethylene overpack in an upright position surrounded by a chemically compatible cushioning/packaging material. It is believed that 2 valves came in contact while in transportation causing one valve to partially open. The escaping oxygen from the cylinder collected in the head space of the container and forced the lid from the package. Our investigation also determined that the polyethylene overpack had the lid securely fastened that allowed the gas to accumulate in the headspace of the package. At the time the container was accepted for transportation no evidence of leakage or pressure build-up was evident. In order to prevent a recurrence, we have initiated a review of the company’s pre-transportation inspection procedures for compressed gas cylinders as well as the guidance document used for the preparation of cylinders for transportation. This document, when updated, will be distributed and reviewed with all applicable personnel and will be incorporated into the company’s training program. In addition, restrictions will be placed on the type, size and quantity of cylinders that can be placed in a single over pack. Finally, all employees involved in the preparation and transportation of this specific shipment were retrained in cylinder handling procedures.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: A PASSING MOTORIST MOTIONED TO OUR DRIVER THAT SOMETHINGS WAS WRONG WITH HIS TRAILER. THE DRIVER  WAS APPROACHING MELE MARKER 62 ON I -70 IN KANSAS, IMMEDIATELY PULLED OFF THE INTERSTATE AND DROVE TO A SAFE HAVE IN THE COUNTY. IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A PRESSURE RELEIF VALVE HAD MALFUNTIONED (DID NOT SHOT ITSELF OFF) CAUSING AN ATMOSPHERIL RELEASE OF 800 GALLON OF ANHYDROUS AMMANIA IN THE AIR. THE KANSAS HWY PATROL AND FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE ON STAND BY, NO ACTION WERE TAKEN NOR WERE THEY NECESSARY. IMMEDIATELY UPON A PHONE CALL TO STRATTON EQUITY COOP, AND EMPTY VESSEL WAS DISPATECHED TO AFFLOAD THE MALFUNCTIONING UNIT. TRAVEL DISTANCE WAS APPROXIMATELY 94 MILES TO THE SITE OF THE INCIDENT. LEPC, KDA KDHEA WERE ALL NOTIFICED , NO ACTION WERE TAKEN.
column169: WE IMPLEMENTAED A MANDATORY INSPECTION  OF ALL PRESSURE LELEIF VALVE. OUR COMPANH IS COMMITTED TO FOLLWING ALL SAFETY PRECAUTIONS, ESPECIALLY INVOLING HA2. MAT., AS WELL AS NANUFACTURE RECOMMENDATION ON EQUIPMENT. WE WELL BE DOING MORE SAFETY AWARENESS TRANING THAT PERTAINS TO PHYSICAL & MECHANICAL ASPECT, OF PRESSURE RELEIF VALVE ON OUR EQUIPMENT. A RE-COCURANCE LIKE THIS IS NOT ANTICIPATED OR ACCETABLE. WE WILL DO ALL THAT IS NECESSARY TO TAKE PREVENTABLE PRECAUTIONS IN THE FUTURE.

column168: DREW OIL DRIVER WAS BOTTOM LOADING DIESEL FUEL. HE WAS LOADING A COMPARTMENT THAT HAD SOME DIESEL IN IT. HE MIS-CALCULATED THE AMOUND NEEDED TO BRING COMPARTMENT UP TO DESIGN CAPACITY. column168: Transport vehicle operated by TransWood Inc. stopped on designated route at mandatory fuel stop.  Truck drivers noticed a mist rising from the manifold cabinet at rear of trailer.  Drivers located vehicle away from persons as practical, notified dispatch of leak, and called 911, evacuated the vehicle with shipping documents and HM information. TransWood notified MEMO and PCS of leaking trailer.  MEMO dispatched Eagle Environmental (contracted response) to the site.  Police, fire and ambulance responded.  TransWood personnel were not allowed in the area to record events or gather information, and the site was handled upon arrival by Eagle Environmental and Preston Summers from LA Hazmat who was acting Incident Commander.                                                      MEMC indicates the following causes of failure:1) Leak through #3 tube isolation valve, through the 1 1/2" feed valve and through the valve cap, 2) Defective air operated valve failed to hold the #3 tube closed, 3) Defective valve stop prevented the 1 1/2" valve from sealing closed, 4) Defective threads on hose cap prevented hose cap from sealing.
column169: TransWood Inc. can make no recommendations to prevent future occurrences. The manifold cabinet is sealed for shipment whether loaded by PCS in Aurora, NC or empty from MEMC Corporation in Pasadena TX.                                 Please find Attachment A, a photo document of the transport vehicle in question and the interior of same manifold cabinet.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, TYPE A PACKAGE NON-SPECIAL FORM, NON FISSILE OR FISSILE-EXCEPTED
column168: At approximately 6:30 AM, a Cardinal Health pickup truck carrying  radiopharmaceuticals rear-ended a tractor trailer (flatbed) which was hauling sod. The accident occurred at the intersection of Hwy 27 and Scenic Highway, just south of Frostproof (Polk County). On board the pickup were several ammo boxes containing  used radiopharmaceutical doses from various medical facilities and 2 ammo boxes  containing unused doses. One of these ammo boxes with unused material contained F-18  destined for Highlands Regional Medical Center, while the other box, contained Tc-99m,and was to go to AT Radiology in Davenport. The driver of the Cardinal vehicle was killed in the accident. Apparently, the driver of the semi was unharmed. Fire consumed the cab of the pickup and much of its bed as well.  Cardinal Health 414, Inc. possesses State of Florida Radioactive Materials License  Number 3453-12, with its facility located at 225 Ave. O, S.W., Winter Haven, FL 33880.
